/repository/AiFeedbackRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/ManagerReviewExceptionRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/WeeklyPlanRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ReconciliationService.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeService.java\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/carryforward/service/CarryForwardServiceTest.java\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockServiceTest.java\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ReconciliationServiceTest.java\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeServiceTest.java\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/steps/18\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/entity/CarryForwardFact.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/entity/ComplianceFact.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/entity/RcdoWeekRollup.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/entity/TeamWeekRollup.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/entity/UserWeekFact.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/CarryForwardFactRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/ComplianceFactRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/RcdoWeekRollupRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/TeamWeekRollupRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/UserWeekFactRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/report\nbackend/src/main/resources/db/migration/V6__add_derived_read_models.sql\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/report\n\nYour session has context from prior steps. The repository may have changed since your last turn.\nBefore making assumptions about file contents, verify the current state of any files you need to modify.\nDo NOT re-read files that are unrelated to the current step.\n\nStep 19: Configuration management and admin settings\n{\n  \"id\": \"step-19\",\n  \"title\": \"Configuration management and admin settings\",\n  \"description\": \"Implement cadence configuration and admin settings per PRD §13 FR-10.\\n\\n**Configuration model:**\\n- `OrgConfig` table: orgId, default week cadence fields (weekStartDay, draftOpenOffset, lockDueOffset, reconcileOpenOffset, reconcileDueOffset), defaultWeeklyBudget, timezone.\\n- `TeamConfigOverride` table: teamId, overridden cadence fields (null = use org default), timezone override.\\n- `CapacityOverride` (already exists from step 8): per-user per-week override.\\n\\n**ConfigurationService:**\\n- `getEffectiveConfig(teamId)`: merges org defaults with team overrides. Returns resolved cadence deadlines for any given week.\\n- `getEffectiveCapacity(userId, weekStart)`: returns user capacity (override > team default > org default, default 10).\\n- `updateOrgConfig(config)`: admin-only.\\n- `updateTeamConfig(teamId, overrides)`: admin or team manager.\\n- Default cadence per PRD §12: planning week Mon-Fri, draft opens Friday 12:00, reconcile opens Friday 17:00, reconcile due Monday 10:00, lock due Monday 12:00.\\n\\n**Integration with lifecycle services:**\\n- Auto-lock job reads effective config to determine cutoff time per team.\\n- Reconcile-open job reads effective config to determine transition time.\\n- Plan creation uses effective capacity for budget snapshot.\\n\\n**Admin settings UI (frontend):**\\n- Admin-only page (accessible from a settings gear icon for Admin role).\\n- Org-level config form: week start day, deadline offsets, default budget.\\n- Team-level overrides: list of teams with override indicators, edit form per team.\\n- Per-user capacity overrides: searchable user list with current/override capacity display.\\n\\n**REST endpoints:**\\n- `GET /api/config/org` — org config\\n- `PUT /api/config/org` — update org config (admin only)\\n- `GET /api/config/teams/{id}` — team config with effective values\\n- `PUT /api/config/teams/{id}` — update team override\\n- `GET /api/config/capacity/{userId}?week=` — effective capacity\\n\\n**Unit tests:** effective config merges org + team correctly, capacity resolution chain (override > team > org > default), lifecycle jobs use per-team deadlines, admin-only access enforced, config changes don't affect already-locked plans.\",\n  \"requiredChecks\": [\n    \"lint\",\n    \"typecheck\",\n    \"unit\",\n    \"build\"\n  ]\n}\n\nYou are the first agent to work on this step.\nImplement the changes described above, run checks to verify, and fix any issues before handing off.\nBe thorough — the next agent will review your work and should find it correct.\n\nPrior observations from earlier steps (address if they fall within this step's scope):\n- [MEDIUM] step 1 backend/build.gradle.kts: Uses Eclipse JDT formatter instead of google-java-format because google-java-format (and palantirJavaFormat) rely on `com.sun.tools.javac.util.Log$DeferredDiagnosticHandler.getDiagnostics()` which was removed in JDK 25. Future steps should be aware of this constraint; a switch to google-java-format would require either downgrading the JDK to ≤24 or waiting for a google-java-format release that supports JDK 25.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/: Mockito's inline mock maker (InlineBytecodeGenerator) is incompatible with JDK 25. Switched to subclass mock maker via the extensions file. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests — not an issue for our service classes but worth noting for future steps.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/resources/mockito-extensions/org.mockito.plugins.MockMaker: Set to `mock-maker-subclass` to work around Mockito inline-mock-maker incompatibility with JDK 25. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests. Not an issue today, but future steps adding mocks of final types will need to handle this.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency is implemented for repeat calls, but the step also called for optimistic locking or compare-and-swap to protect concurrent runners. I did not see explicit concurrency protection beyond state checks.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency relies only on a state check (DRAFT guard). There is no database-level optimistic lock (`@Version`) to protect against concurrent auto-lock runners. This is acceptable for v1 given single-instance deployment, but a future step should add `@Version` to `WeeklyPlan` and a Flyway migration for the `version` column if concurrent scheduling ever becomes a concern.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ReconciliationService.java: The `getReconciliationView` method allows state RECONCILING or RECONCILED, but `setCommitOutcome` only allows RECONCILING. If a manager views a RECONCILED plan via `getReconciliationView`, then tries to `setCommitOutcome`, they get a 400. This is correct behavior but worth documenting clearly in the API.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeService.java: The `removePostLockCommit` method sets `outcome = CANCELED` immediately (pre-reconciliation). During `submitReconciliation`, this commit is treated as already having an outcome (CANCELED), which is correct. However, calling `setCommitOutcome` on an already-CANCELED (removed) commit during RECONCILING would allow overriding the post-lock cancellation — a guard could prevent this in a future step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: Peer visibility is filtered at the field level (PeerCommitView strips sensitive fields) but the \"current and next week only\" temporal constraint for peer callers is not enforced at the service layer — a peer can request any historical week. Not a breaking issue for v1 but worth tightening in a future step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: `checkCanAccessTeam` requires the caller to be a team member. An ADMIN-managed parent team manager without explicit membership in a child team would be blocked from viewing that child team's data. This is consistent with current behavior but the \"indirect reports' aggregates\" capability from the step spec is not fully exercised in the team-week endpoint.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: Peer visibility appears field-filtered, but the “current and next week only” peer time-window rule may not be enforced server-side for arbitrary requested weeks.\n- [MEDIUM] step 12 frontend/src/routes/MyWeek.tsx: The pre-lock validation panel derives soft warnings client-side from commit data, but the actual hard-error list only appears AFTER the lock attempt returns validation errors. This means the user sees the panel before errors are shown. A dedicated `GET /api/plans/{id}/validate` endpoint could provide server-side validation without actually locking, giving immediate feedback. This is a future enhancement.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/components/teamweek/ByRcdoSection.tsx: The ByRcdoSection only shows `totalPoints` (planned) per RCDO node since the backend's `RcdoRollupEntry` doesn't include achieved points. A future enhancement could add achieved point rollup to the backend DTO.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: The step calls for a manager team selector for users who can manage multiple teams, but the current host bridge only exposes `currentTeam` and the route param, not a selectable team list. The dashboard currently supports route-based team selection, but not an in-page selector.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: ByPersonSection supports `onVie